 also consider the lives of boys such as chimney sweeps and convicted criminals, whose bodily labor was considered their only value and who often did not live beyond boyhood. Defined by a variety of tasks, expectations, and objectifications, boys—real, imagined, and sometimes both—were subject to the control of their elders and were used as tools in the cause of civil society, commerce, and empire. This book argues that boys in the long eighteenth century constituted a particular kind of currency, both valuable and expendable—valuable because of gender, expendable because of youth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBoys in literature2DLC. 0aBoys in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century2DLC. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  agender studies, masculinity studies, labor studies, history of labor, labor history, bodily labor, childhood studies, boyhood, childhood, youth, eighteenth-century studies, the long eighteenth century, literary studies, English literature, Enlightenment literature, chimney sweeps, apprentices, apprenticeship, printer's devils, automatons.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z978311131826440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978164453322240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644533222423Coveruhttps://www.de